---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p><em>We have implemented a dynamic orchestration layer to decompose and execute search strategies for Van der Waerden (VdW) partition boundaries.</em></p>

<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>Extremal combinatorics problems, such as determining Van der Waerden numbers, present significant challenges for standard heuristic search. While graph-theoretic bounds often operate on adjacency matrices, locating monochromatic-free partitions for arithmetic progressions (e.g., $W(5, 3) > 170$) requires a specialized topological representation. </p>

<p>The objective was to transition from rigid, hardcoded search environments to a generalized Hub-and-Spoke orchestration model. In this framework, the central Architect hub structurally maps the mathematical constraints and delegates specific sub-tasks to specialized spokes.</p>

<h2>Architecture and Implementation</h2>
<p>The Perqed orchestrator was extended to handle 1D integer-partition networks by refining the Architect's decomposition logic and adding specialized optimization spokes.</p>

<ol>
<li><strong>Constraint Decomposition</strong>: The Architect processes the high-level research goal and isolates the combinatorial parameters. For a target like $W(k, r)$, it defines the domain size, the number of partitions ($k$), and the target progression length ($r$).</li>
<li><strong>Algebraic Initialization</strong>: Instead of purely stochastic initialization, the system utilizes an <strong>Algebraic Spoke</strong> to generate declarative rules based on modular symmetries. This provides a high-density structural baseline for the search.</li>
<li><strong>Hybrid Search Execution</strong>: The Architect delegates the refined search space to a <strong>Heuristic Spoke</strong>, which utilizes Simulated Annealing (SA) to navigate the partition landscape. The SA engine mutates the initial algebraic skeleton to minimize the "energy" (the count of monochromatic progressions).</li>
<li><strong>Verification and Formalization</strong>: Upon locating a potential witness (Energy = 0), the results are passed to the <strong>Verification Spoke</strong>. Due to the computational complexity of formalizing large-scale index arithmetic in Lean 4, the system utilizes a tiered approach: empirical validation of the witness followed by targeted formal verification of the underlying combinatorial properties.</li>
</ol>

<p>This Hub-and-Spoke model allows the system to autonomously map abstract constraints into bounded search spaces, leveraging both algebraic symmetry and heuristic optimization to find witnesses for complex extremal bounds.</p>
`;
